def merge_alternately(word1, word2):
    merged = []
    i, j = 0, 0
    while i < len(word1) or j < len(word2):
        if i < len(word1):
            merged.append(word1[i])
            i += 1
        if j < len(word2):
            merged.append(word2[j])
            j += 1
    return "".join(merged)
```

    The algorithm initializes two pointers, i and j, starting from 0. We will move through word1 with i and word2 with j. The merged string is initialized as an empty string or a list of characters, depending on the language.

In a while loop, we check if either i or j is still within its respective string length. Inside the loop, we first check if i is within the length of word1. If so, we append the character at position i in word1 to the merged string and increment i. Similarly, we check if j is within the length of word2. If so, we append the character at position j in word2 to the merged string and increment j.

After both i and j have reached the end of their respective strings, we return the merged string.

